What Is ARIA and When to Use It

01
On this page
  1. What is ARIA
  2. The Rules of ARIA
  3. Who is Using What?
    1. Screen Readers
    2. Accessibility Support

What is ARIA

ARIA stands for “Accessible Rich Internet Applications” and it comes from a specification.

The specification lists a standard set of attributes that you can plumb into your webpages for accessibility information.

"Standard" means you can't make up your own attributes and there are requirements for using them on specific elements or in combinations.

ARIA is an advanced level tool that we reach for when we're creating custom UI components on the web.

The Rules of ARIA

The first rule of ARIA is essentially “Don’t use ARIA.”

What that really is saying is that you should always default to using a native HTML element or attribute that already includes the semantics or behavior you need.

Using a div and adding ARIA to isn’t always as good as using a native element. Plus, native elements give you a lot of functionality for free. A lot of developers choose to build custom controls because of style-ability, but they lose out on accessibility wins in the process. Choosing a native element for its functionality will ultimately save you time, and time is money.

There are additional rules of ARIA that are very worth reading: https://www.w3.org/TR/using-aria/

When you apply ARIA, you have to test and make sure it works with Assistive Technology. Plenty of teams have learned about ARIA, then started adding it to everything without realizing that under the hood it was having a negative impact on accessibility.

The Axe DevTools and Accessibility Insights extensions help highlight common issues. However, it is still possible for an application to not have issues detected but still provide a horrible user experience in a screen reader.

Ultimately, the end goal for ARIA really is to add accessibility information that benefits screen reader users so that they can understand what’s on a page and how to interact with it.

Who is Using What?

When it comes to ARIA, it’s important to keep in mind the different platforms our users are on as some may behave differently. ARIA attributes unfortunately aren’t universally supported and require testing to ensure users won’t miss out on important context.

Screen Readers

Note: Screenshots are from Screen Reader Survey version 9.

Based on this data along with your own browser analytics, you can prioritize which combinations to test in your own application.

If 80% of your mobile traffic comes from iOS Safari, it stands to reason that testing it with mobile VoiceOver would be a good idea.

Accessibility Support

The community-driven Accessibility Support site at a11ysupport.io is a super useful resource to check out which ARIA features are supported in various combinations on different platforms.

Here’s an example that shows support for aria-label:

In the above example, we can see that aria-label is generally supported by screen readers for the default, with a partial exception for Edge. Support does waver when an aria-label value is changed when an element is focused, such as on a toggle button.
